\chapter{Conclusions}\label{chap:conclusion}

In this thesis, we have described an extension to the logic of HOL-based theorem provers to support a module system that enables theorem reuse. We have also explored proving correctness of the proposed design. The implementation has been integrated into the Candle source code written in the HOL4 theorem prover, and the correctness theorems written in terms of the existing verified sources of the Candle project. 

Many limitations of the project exist; however, it seems feasible for future work to extend this to an extent under which the contribution could become a useful feature for everyday proving in HOL-based ITPs. We have presented some key limitations in Section \ref{sect:limitations}, and discussed ways to remedy them in Chapter \ref{chap:future-work}.

As we have stated before, modules in theorem proving are certainly not a novel concept. In the late 1990s to early 2010s, mainstream theorem provers tackled their solutions to theorem proving module systems. However, it was only in the mid 2010s that the comprehensive verification of theorem provers became of particular interest. We present our contribution in a modern-day context, where it is more feasible than ever to make more guarantees during theorem prover development. We have now described and justified an implementation specification for a new module system for the HOL-family of ITPs, and begun a mechanised verification unlike what has been done before. It remains incomplete, but we have discussed how the work could be continued in the future from our contribution of a large library of theorems written about the system.